<dl id="n36180j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36180j">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36180j"> 180(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> shall in the second Adam all be / made alive ~ <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n36180j"><li>FW 551.22 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/lexrB.htm#n36180j">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/l39rB.htm#n36180j">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n36180j">MS BL 47484b-454</ms> </li><li>JJA 59:197 <a name="rBd14" href="../../FF/fdra/rda.htm#rBd14">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rB/rBd14.htm#n36180j">Draft: III&sect;3B.14</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The Darkness. The Homeless]</font> Work, work! it is always work that they ask. The Divine curse is to them the most blessed of benedictions. &ldquo;In the sweat of thy brow thou shalt eat thy bread,&rdquo; but alas for these forlorn sons of Adam, they fail to find the bread to eat, for Society has no work for them to do. They have not even leave to sweat. As well as discussing how these poor wanderers <mark>should in the second Adam &ldquo;all be made alive</mark>,&rdquo; ought we not to put forth some effort to effect their restoration to that share in the heritage of lab our which is theirs by right of descent from the first Adam? <small> William Booth, <a name="WBDE" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#WBDE"><cite title="source">In Darkest England and the Way Out</cite></a> (1893) Part 1, Chapter 3</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
